<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> element is used to provide fallback parentheses for browsers that do not support display of ruby annotations using the <a href="/docs/elements/native/ruby/"><code>&lt;ruby&gt;</code></a> element. The content of <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> is typically parentheses, but can be any text that helps indicate the annotation.</p>
    <p>In browsers that support ruby, the content of <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> is hidden. In browsers without ruby support, it's displayed, wrapping the annotation text in parentheses (or whatever characters you provide).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Basic Example</h2>
    <div class="example">
      <ruby>
        漢字 <rp>(</rp><rt>かんじ</rt><rp>)</rp>
      </ruby>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Basic rp example">{{ basicRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How It Renders</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> element provides graceful degradation:</p>
    <code-block language="text" label="Rendering comparison">{{ supportedRenderingCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why Use rp?</h2>
    <p>Without <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code>, browsers that don't support ruby will show confusing output:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="With vs without rp">{{ withoutRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Multiple Annotations</h2>
    <p>Each ruby text should have its own pair of rp elements:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <ruby>
        東 <rp>(</rp><rt>とう</rt><rp>)</rp>
        京 <rp>(</rp><rt>きょう</rt><rp>)</rp>
      </ruby>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Multiple annotations">{{ multipleRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Alternative Characters</h2>
    <p>You can use brackets or other characters instead of parentheses:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <ruby>
        日本 <rp>[</rp><rt>にほん</rt><rp>]</rp>
      </ruby>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Brackets instead of parentheses">{{ bracketRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Attributes</h2>
    <p>This element supports <a href="/docs/elements/native/states/">global attributes</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> content is typically hidden from screen readers in browsers that support ruby. In non-supporting environments, the parentheses help clarify that the text in them is an annotation of the preceding text.</p>
  </section>

